EXT. WOODS - DAY

She has the woods all nice and lush. She has a bookshelf with all of the classics on it and reads sitting next to the lake. She listens to classical music while dancing by the late and is euphoric.

There is one moment that I haven't imagined yet where she realizes that being completely alone is not good. But it is a single expression with a narration from her journal that delivers this idea.

She has an AI voice that she is talking to. The she is trying to hold conversation with it but it is unrewarding and pointless. She says that because it has no physical form, she began to mistake it for her own internal monologue and started to hate herself.

She introduces a form but there is another issue with this which forces her to realize that the only way to get the result she's after is by getting another human being.

She is walking around the lake with her friend giving her the sales pitch of her reality. The friend is impressed with what's she's been able to build. Mirabel asks her friend if she would like to contribute a copy of her consciousness to her reality. The friend answers no on the principal that she believes that being aware of the fact the you are in a simulation is fundamentally flawed, especially when combined with the lack of a "death" mechanism. She tells her that she will go insane and try to escape no matter how many books she has. She apologizes and leaves. Mirabel is left there to contemplate.

